2020 was a year that has pushed us in innumerable ways. Over at The Loveland Foundation we have been unrelenting in our efforts to get mental health care access to as many Black women and girls as possible.
•
My team and I are gearing up for what we hope is a successful Giving Tuesday push tomorrow as we seek raise more funds which equals more hours of therapy for our recipients. I hope you’ll consider @thelovelandfoundation as part of your 2020 community investment.
•
We asked our cohort members and therapists to tell us: Why does your mental health matter? We are excited to share with you some of their responses.
•
I am beyond proud of the Black women and girls who are prioritizing their mental health this year.
•
I am so grateful to and proud of you all for loving on yourselves, cherishing yourselves and prioritizing your wellbeing this year and beyond.
•
Support this post getting a boost in the Internet atmosphere by dropping a comment and sharing with your communities! And be sure to follow @thelovelandfoundation to get details for tomorrow’s Giving Tuesday donation drive!

node.text:
In the time between when the pandemic began and when the protests began I spent time every weekday reading stories to little ones who may have tuned in.
•
As someone without children I often feel like it’s my obligation to be part of the “village” that helps other‘s in providing care for theirs. The reading series I did had been my way of showing up where I can and where I feel led to.
•
It’s the same now in this continued fight against injustice and this particular fight against police brutality — we all have to show up whenever and however and with every ounce of our power, heart and intention.
•
I wanted to offer this reading I did just a few weeks ago by Faith Ringgold as a soft space in your day — whenever this post may pop up on your feed.
•
I say over and over my healing has always been found in Black women and book written and illustrated by Faith Ringgold has held my heart tenderly since my own mama read it to me as a little girl. Today Cassie and her dreams and her words and her hopes for her people still sound like the sweetest thing to my ears and encompasses the passions I hold within me.
•
Take a breath, listen to the story, continue to show up and never back down.
•
If you love this book you can purchase it from my bookstore @elizabethsofakron and a parentage of proceeds will go to @thelovelandfoundation.

Please share. We’ve got rest to do 🌙
•
After falling into a restful weekend of my own last year, I got in touch with @getawayhouse to see how we could get more black people in safe and replenishing spaces. We found success in developing a impactful partnership that we called #100nightsofrest (which shape-shifted into #AYearOfRest) and were able to grant people on the front lines a night of rest that they deserve — free of cost and with things like transportation and food cost covered.
•
As demands for accountability from racist institutions, social unrest and powerful protests continue we went back to the drawing board to see how we could extend our efforts. I’m exited to partner with @getawayhouse and @mailchimp to relaunch our efforts with Year of Rest.
•
We received thousands of nominations last year and are recommiting this year to provide another 365 days of rest for those within the Black community fighting for change - from artists and educators, to activists and entrepreneurs.  Watch this video to learn more about the power of rest and at the link in my bio you will find a nomination form and more information about our partnership and this small but really meaningful step toward reminding black people that rest, too, is part of the revolution.
•
#ayearofrest

I found this journal entry from 2016 and it made this heart of mine existing in 2021 just melt. Re-reading my words reminds me of the most true tenets of myself. The ones that never seem to ween away. 

Dec 21, 2016: “I'm not in search of happiness. For that I'm thankful. I've learned to cultivate that on my own. Organically grown within myself.

It's simplicity that I'm craving to develop deep roots in over the next few years. Society makes things so complex. I'm far too free of a woman to stress over invisible rules. I like to do as I please as long I maintain my authenticity, my kindness, my meaningful approach to living.

So I'm scaling back on a lot of things. Becoming minimal in order to maximize on the WAY I want to live, the FEELINGS I want to soak in, the EXPERIENCES that will enrich me. 

Community and freedom are the two biggest values in my life right now. That's a constant and as I'm growing those are shining through more strongly. I'm grateful.”

There is more for me to do, more ways for me to grow, more of a legacy for me to form, more knowledge for me to gain then share. So when I have those moments of quiet and space please know it's for good and if you notice more activism/teaching/writing and less personal stuff please share and engage in conversation because that is for good and if I'm not always uber available please know that it's for good because I know that being my best self is my highest service and I can assure you that being my best self is all I'm spending my time doing.”

#eternalsunday

node.text:
Swipe 📚Just your local bookshop owner relishing in a full year of community & nourishment here in my hometown of Akron, Ohio!
•
My company The Loveland Group and all of our ventures including my bookshop & writing centre @elizabethsofakron celebrating one year of community, service and possibility. We decided to hold this celebration right there in Akron (where my bookshop lives!).
•
If you’re here in NorhEast Ohio please join us as you’re able to for time at the art museum (free entry as we celebrate!) and story time in the bookstore with me and my mom! Registration links to these free events are in my bio.
•
Tomorrow night I’ll be live in conversation with the incredible @nifmuhammad at the bookstore to relish in his genius and the value of being here back home in Ohio.
•
I’m so grateful for the ways younger versions of myself dreamed up ways for this version of myself to show up in the world. Look where we’ve landed! Look how we’ve grown! I hope you’ll come celebrate with me ♥️

Swipe 🌿 What is your relationship been with self advocacy?
•
I made a post a while back about how I had been taught to curate the tool of self advocacy at a very young age. [See the last slide of this post for a photo of a precious letter I wrote my teacher in grade school] This was a particular cultivation of:
.
1. Understanding that asking for help was an act of self love 2. I truly BELIEVED I deserved clarity and understanding as I move through life.
•
There were so many intimate comments from parents and teachers and readers of mine of all ages who expressed that this is an ongoing skill they are cultivating for themselves and  the people around them so I wanted to offer a soft and simple set of, what I call “conversation on-ramps” to perhaps assist in strengthening that self advocacy muscle in the form of questions.
•
If you have interest in screenshotting, printing or downloading these for use and share in your home or classroom feel free to and if you’ve the ability consider donating/contributing to my work tangibly through the options listed in the “SUPPORT” tab of my highlights (I will also add to my stories for today) 🌿
•
I’m a teacher at heart and when interacting with readers/students/classmates I know language and communication are our greatest tools for bridging all types of gaps. I take it very seriously. Tag those who might find this tool valuable to their experiences as well.
•

Insight from the lovely mind of @deeperthandesigner:
…
Today Jeff Bezos shot himself up into space because he has nothing better to do with his billions. 

In reading the headlines this morning, I was reminded of the 1970 spoken word piece written and performed by poet and recording artist, Gil Scott-Heron titled ‘Whitey on The Moon”. Between 1969 and 1972, the Apollo Program dispatched the first humans to ever land on the moon. The total program cost was estimated at 28 billion dollars, or 280 billion if you adjust for inflation. 

The mid sixties and seventies also brought about the Black Arts Movement. A cultural love child produced by the Black Power movement and the Black artists whose work reflected the social and political happenings of the era. Scott-Heron being heavily influenced by the Black Arts Movement was a musician and spoken word performer who spread the struggle of being a Black man in America over his lyrics and throughout all of his artistic projects. ‘Whitey on The Moon’, recorded in 1970 is one of his most notable pieces, and is still being uncovered by generations of art enthusiasts of all kinds. Most recently, the recording was featured in the second episode of Lovecraft Country. 

The first and second stanzas read:

A rat done bit my sister Nell. 
(with Whitey on the moon) 
Her face and arms began to swell. 
(and Whitey's on the moon)

I can't pay no doctor bill. 
(but Whitey's on the moon) 
Ten years from now I'll be payin' still. 
(while Whitey's on the moon)

Over 50 years have passed since that initial investment was made to put a total of 24 Whiteys on The Moon while the conditions of many Black and Brown neighborhoods have not changed, (and have worsened in some). The amount of money that continues to be spent on wildly unnecessary rich boy “adventures” proves that the exorbitantly wealthy population are without morals and should be criminalized and not glorified IN ANY WAY.

A laughable quote from Bozo to top it off:

“To see the Earth from space, it changes you. It changes your relationship with this planet, with humanity. It’s one Earth.”

Clap it up for yourself Jeff, you’re a true American hero.

node.text:
swipe 💫 The version of me that simply gets to exist as a Black girl from Ohio with memories of being 15 and sitting on sidewalks outside our apartment as the midwest sun beats on my back while I read the magazine I begged my mom to buy me from the display in the grocery store checkout lane — that girl is squealing a bit. You can find me in Allure Magazine this month sharing a bit of my beauty routine.
•
I’m realizing that it makes some people uncomfortable to witness me exist outside of being their “antiracism educator”. They take offense to my existence being anything else other than in direct relation to their whiteness. And sometimes the feeling sneaks up on them.
•
I want to address this for a moment — especially in the context of such a fun and frivolous post like my skin routine being featured in a magazine.
•
There is something I need you to know: I am intentional about using this lifetime to find chance after chance to reinvent myself. To find a plethora of ways to express my values, my beliefs, my creativity, my interests and my passions. I am inspired by the opportunity to reimagine the ways I can exist meaningfully and in rhythm with my morals and with the ease and abundance I believe I deserve as a human being. 
•
So….prepare your heart for when I decide to push my own limits and possibilities. When I dip into various version of myself that may craft a romance novel or farm the land near my home or go on sabbatical for 3 years or take a guest professorship at your local college or produce a children’s book series or collaborate on a clothing line or produce a documentary or open an ice cream parlor or reinvent myself in some other way that doesn’t fit inside the box you needed me to be in for your own comfort.
•
I’m here to fight, to think, to be in community and conversation. I’m here to learn and to teach and swoon over the things I adore about the living. I’m here to live.
•
And the deepest desire of my heart is that when I do, it means I am writing the permission slip you’ve been looking for (but never really needed) to do the same.
•
Q: What are some ways you’ve reinvented yourself lately?

Swipe 🥨 This is an appreciation post for this body of mine. Descriptors of my 5'9" frame include: Tall, brown, fat, soft, and curvy. I love my body. I love the way it moves when I dance, the way it has carried me for 32 years, and the way it changes over time.
•
A few years ago I wrote a piece for @harpersbazaarus about my frustrations around the way people called this shoot “brave”. I didn’t feel brave — I needn’t be, I wasn’t running into a burning building! What I actually felt was sexy and joyous. Then calling me brave said more about their perceptions of my fat body than anything having to do with my own “courage” to be bare.
•
photo by my sweet sweet friend @sarahbahbah 
•
You can head to the link in my bio to read the full essay.
•
For more of my writing you can head to my blog AnEternalSunday.com where my comments are open and I’m so ready to be in community with you all over there. (link in bio as well)

My followers had seen the depths of my mind, so this body shouldn't have rocked too many boats.'.

Swipe 🌿 A Sunday Moodboard +  my new blog.
•
I shared with you all last week the feelings I’d been swimming in around social platforms. How disenchanting it’s all become. About how I wanted to reimagine the way I am in community.
•
So I did. I reimagined. You can head to the link in my bio and find it: ‘Something Like An Eternal Sunday’. It’s a space where my writing can live with some softness and simplicity. See you there?
•
The first six posts are published for you. These are all writings done by previous and varying versions of myself. I hope you read them and perhaps add some texture to the ways you engage with me and my work. I share my entry essay to Columbia and a letter I wrote to myself in 2017. I share a piece where I questioned humanity on the NYC subway and I share the essay on the song my mother used to hum for me — an audio of the song was recorded by my mother and you listen to her love for me.
•
Head over, spend a few moments of YOUR soft Sunday reading my words and let me know what you think.
•
Im settling into very very new versions of myself. Im looking forward to growing along with you — just not so much in these little squares anymore. Join me IRL and online via my brands @thegreatunlearn & @tguyounglearners & @elizabethsofakron & @richauntiesupreme. These are places here we gather and we build and we learn and we grow. I’m not here to make content. I want to build community. I hope you’ll join me off the timeline. My blog is a really good place to start. 
•
In the meantime this set of photos are highlights that have been on my mind. Gifts from my garden, the birdsong that melted my heart this morning, smiles from lovers and friends, solo lunches in Chinatown and some art literature I can’t get enough of.
•
See you around 💫
•
But before you go: What sweetness found it’s way into your Sunday today?

node.text:
Social media is disenchanting me  more and more.

I’m leaning into slow and simple and soft and easeful. 

I’m a writer. I’m an entrepreneur. I’m a creative. I’m a friend. Im a lover. I’m a daughter. I’m an auntie. I’m a reader. I’m a neighbor. I’m a student. I’m a teacher. 

Influencer & a content creator just don’t fit me well.

I’m a Black girl curating a good life for me. Im not seeking for this lifetime of mine to simply be seen or validated. I want it to be lived — indulgently. Im uninterested in only being gazed upon in small squares.

I feel things shifting in me.

I’m craving something like an eternal Sunday.
🌿

I said “eternal Sunday” on a whim while writing this but it is such a spot on concept for the soft space I’m trying to create. I’m thinking of indulging in starting a blog where I can write long form and share my ideas and my insights and all the good things happening in my world — And IG will instead be a place where I signal boost what’s happening in my real world instead of the platform being where it all resides. Would you be interested in following my work & check in with me outside this platform? I have a book coming soon, many exciting partnerships to share and lots of delicious workshops, conversations and lectures on my horizon that I’d continue to let you know about on your timeline — but the roots of my no longer have space to spread in these boxes. Maybe Ill just lost in Sunday’s to touch base, catch up? Let me know your thoughts 🧡 Just some active reimagining with you all this morning. I’m so happy you’re here and I don’t take this community for granted one bit….
